First, you need to include the necessary headers and the `markdown` library in your project. You can install the `markdown` library using a package manager like `pip` for Python, or you can include it directly in your C++ project.

Here's how you can implement the function:

1. Include the necessary headers.
2. Create the function that takes a reference to a `std::string` containing markdown formatted text.
3. Use the `markdown` library to parse the markdown and convert it to HTML.
4. Return the HTML formatted text as a `std::string`.

To include the `markdown` library, you can use a precompiled library if available. For example, if you are using Python, you can install the `markdown` library using `pip install markdown`.

Here's a complete example in C++:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <markdown/markdown.h>
#include <markdown/markdown_basic.h>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdownText) {
    // Initialize the markdown library
    markdown_init();

    // Create a parser for markdown
    markdown_context* ctx = markdown_context_new();

    // Parse the markdown text
    std::string htmlText = markdown_parse(markdownText.c_str(), ctx);

    // Clean up the parser and context
    markdown_context_free(ctx);
    markdown_cleanup();

    return htmlText;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdownText = "# Hello Markdown\n\nThis is some text.\n";
    std::string htmlText = markdownToHtml(markdownText);
    std::cout << "Markdown:\n" << markdownText << "\n\nHTML:\n" << htmlText << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

Make sure you have the `markdown` library available. For Python, you can use a precompiled binary or install it using `pip install markdown`.

This example uses the `markdown` library in C++ to parse the markdown text and convert it to HTML. The `markdown_init` and `markdown_cleanup` functions are used to initialize and clean up the markdown library properly.

Creating a smooth snake game in C with images for animation involves several steps, including setting up your environment, handling user input, managing the game state, and rendering the game on-screen. Below is a simplified guide to help you get started with a basic implementation.

### Step-by-Step Guide

#### 1. Set Up Your Environment
First, ensure you have the necessary development environment set up. You'll need a C compiler like `gcc`.

#### 2. Create the Main Program
Create a main file, e.g., `snake.c`, and set up the basic structure.

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <conio.h>
#include <windows.h>
#include <time.h>

#define WIDTH 20
#define HEIGHT 20

typedef struct {
    int x, y;
} Point;

typedef struct {
    int head, tail;
    Point pos[3];
} Snake;

Snake snake;
Point food;
int direction, delay = 500;

void initGame();
void displayGame();
void updateGame();
void handleInput();

int main() {
    initGame();
    while (1) {
        displayGame();
        handleInput();
        updateGame();
        Sleep(delay);
    }
    return 0;
}
```

#### 3. Define Functions
Define the necessary functions to handle the game logic and rendering.

```c
void initGame() {
    snake.head = 0;
    snake.tail = 1;
    snake.pos[0].x = WIDTH / 2;
    snake.pos[0].y = HEIGHT / 2;
    srand(time(NULL));
    food.x = rand() % WIDTH;
    food.y = rand() % HEIGHT;
    direction = 1; // Right
}

void displayGame() {
    system("cls"); // system("clear") for Linux/Mac
    for (int i = 0; i < WIDTH; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < HEIGHT; j++) {
            if (i == snake.pos[snake.head].x && j == snake.pos[snake.head].y) {
                printf("O");
            } else if (i == food.x && j == food.y) {
                printf("O");
            } else {
                printf(".");
            }
        }
        printf("\n");
    }
}

void updateGame() {
    int nextHead = (snake.head + direction) % 3;
    Point newPos = {snake.pos[nextHead].x, snake.pos[nextHead].y};
    snake.pos[snake.tail] = newPos;

    if (nextHead == 0) {
        food.x = (snake.pos[snake.head].x + 1) % WIDTH;
        food.y = snake.pos[snake.head].y;
    } else if (nextHead == 1) {
        food.x = (snake.pos[snake.head].x - 1) % WIDTH;
        food.y = snake.pos[snake.head].y;
    } else if (nextHead == 2) {
        food.y = (snake.pos[snake.head].y + 1) % HEIGHT;
        food.x = snake.pos[snake.head].x;
    } else if (nextHead == 3) {
        food.y = (snake.pos[snake.head].y - 1) % HEIGHT;
        food.x = snake.pos[snake.head].x;
    }

    if (food.x == snake.pos[snake.head].x && food.y == snake.pos[snake.head].y) {
        delay *= 2;
        if (delay > 3000) delay = 3000;
    } else {
        snake.tail = (snake.tail + 1) % 3;
    }

    if (snake.tail == 0) {
        if (direction == 1) snake.pos[snake.tail].x = snake.pos[snake.head].x - 1;
        if (direction == 2) snake.pos[snake.tail].x = snake.pos[snake.head].x + 1;
        if (direction == 3) snake.pos[snake.tail].y = snake.pos[snake.head].y - 1;
        if (direction == 4) snake.pos[snake.tail].y = snake.pos[snake.head].y + 1;
    }
}

void handleInput() {
    if (_kbhit()) {
        switch (_getch()) {
            case 'a':
                direction = 2;
                break;
            case 'd':
                direction = 4;
                break;
            case 'w':
                direction = 3;
                break;
            case 's':
                direction = 1;
                break;
        }
    }
}
```

#### 4. Handle Input and Update Game
In the `handleInput` function, you can handle user input to change the direction of the snake.

#### 5. Main Function
The main function initializes the game, displays it, and handles updates and inputs.

### Notes
- **Graphics Library**: This example uses `system("cls")` to clear the screen. For a graphical library like SDL, you would use `SDL_RenderClear` and `SDL_RenderCopy`.
- **Game Logic**: The game logic is simplified for demonstration purposes. You can add more features like score tracking, obstacles, or different levels.
- **Smooth Animation**: For smooth animations, you might need to use a library like SDL, SFML, or other game development frameworks.

### Conclusion
This guide gives you a basic framework to start with. Depending on your needs, you can expand and refine the game to make it smoother and more polished.

